trying again, and again and again. My suggestion is to test DTMF output from a variety of devices into the 8870 (the DTMF decoding chip). You\'ll find a sweet spot that will work for all of the devices. Too much gain, and you\'ll get nothing. Too little gain, and you\'ll miss digits. In this process, I was constantly changing up the breadboard, hence the ton of test leads.\n\nIn that video you\'ll see that what I\'m decoding is output in binary on 4 LEDs. You\'ll see the pattern cycling through counting from 0 to 15. (Or if you need a refresher on <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_numeral_system#Counting_in_binary\">counting in binary, wikipedia can help</a>)\n\nThe DTMF output example sketch from the Tone Library is nice, doubly so in that it <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/867-5309/Jenny\">outpulses 867-5309, Jenny</a> (factoid: Most people think <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/555_(telephone_number)\">the 555 fictional exchange</a> came about because of that song, but, it only caused a gain in demand for fictional numbers due to it). Is there any other number you should first decode? Historians have unilaterally decided: No.\n\nI\'ve got <a href=\"http://www.pasteall.org/29962/c\">some demo code</a> from when I was first decoding from the 8870, if it comes in handy.','tapeDuino: breadboard purgatory!','','inherit','open','open','','11-autosave','','','2012-03-13 12:50:15','2012-03-13 12:50:15','',11,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=18',0,'revision','',0),(19,1,'2012-03-12 13:53:08','2012-03-12 13:53:08','<iframe src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/MZBvprynRvQ\" frameborder=\"0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\"></iframe>\r\n\r\nThen... Out comes the breadboard. And, whoa! It\'s in a state of disarray. For a while, one of the first things I bumped into was the op amp circuitry in the IC. It took quite a bit of turning, throwing in and tearing out pots, tuning them, trying again, and again and again.\r\n\r\nOf course, what\'s the first thing a man\'s to do when he\'s decoding DTMF? He\'s gotta decode 867-5309. I mean, it\'s Jenny\'s number. Is there any other number you should first decode? Historians have unilaterally decided: No.','tapeDuino: breadboard purgatory!','','inherit','open','open','','11-revision-7','','','2012-03-12 13:53:08','2012-03-12 13:53:08','',11,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=19',0,'revision','',0),(20,1,'2012-03-12 14:07:33','2012-03-12 14:07:33','This is supposed to be an about page, with cool quotes like:\n<blockquote>\"Uh oh\" -Doug</blockquote>\n...or something like this:\n<blockquote>\"I love my wife, especially when she loves Arduino projects!\" -Doug</blockquote>\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!','About','','inherit','open','open','','2-autosave','','','2012-03-12 14:07:33','2012-03-12 14:07:33','',2,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=20',0,'revision','',0),(21,1,'2012-03-09 20:52:18','2012-03-09 20:52:18','This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:\n\n<blockquote>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my blog. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</blockquote>\n\n...or something like this:\n\n<blockquote>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickies to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</blockquote>\n\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!','Sample Page','','inherit','open','open','','2-revision','','','2012-03-09 20:52:18','2012-03-09 20:52:18','',2,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=21',0,'revision','',0),(22,1,'2012-03-12 01:53:41','2012-03-12 01:53:41','','Shopping Cart','','inherit','open','open','','7-revision','','','2012-03-12 01:53:41','2012-03-12 01:53:41','',7,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=22',0,'revision','',0),(23,1,'2012-03-12 14:06:01','2012-03-12 14:06:01','<iframe src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/MZBvprynRvQ\" frameborder=\"0\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\"></iframe>\r\n\r\nThen... Out comes the breadboard. And, whoa! It\'s in a state of disarray. For a while, one of the first things I bumped into was the op amp circuitry in the IC. It took quite a bit of turning, throwing in and tearing out pots, tuning them, trying again, and again and again. My suggestion is to test DTMF output from a variety of devices into the 8870 (the DTMF decoding chip). You\'ll find a sweet spot that will work for all of the devices. Too much gain, and you\'ll get nothing. Too little gain, and you\'ll miss digits. In this process, I was constantly changing up the breadboard, hence the ton of test leads.\r\n\r\nOf course, what\'s the first thing a man\'s to do when he\'s decoding DTMF? He\'s gotta decode 867-5309. I mean, it\'s Jenny\'s number. Is there any other number you should first decode? Historians have unilaterally decided: No.\r\n\r\nI\'ve got <a href=\"http://www.pasteall.org/29962/c\">some demo code</a> from when I was first decoding from the 8870, if it comes in handy.','tapeDuino: breadboard purgatory!','','inherit','open','open','','11-revision-8','','','2012-03-12 14:06:01','2012-03-12 14:06:01','',11,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=23',0,'revision','',0),(24,1,'2012-03-12 12:13:55','2012-03-12 12:13:55','<a href=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/schematic-tapeDuino-Integrated-v2_bb.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-9 alignleft\" title=\"schematic - tapeDuino Integrated v2\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/schematic-tapeDuino-Integrated-v2_bb-300x200.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /></a>Over a course of visits to the studio space I share... I kept seeing an old school cassette walkman, and a bunch of (bad) old tapes on the desk of one of my space-mates. After some time passed, I thought he was maybe building a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commodore_Datasette\">datasette</a><a href=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/schematic-tapeDuino-Integrated-v2_bb.png\"> clone. </a> I loved the C64 Datasette! I was a bit too young to own my own, however I was envious of my cousin\'s datasette, man, too cool.\r\n\r\nThat, ummm, wasn\'t the case at all. In fact, I\'m still not sure why he\'s got the tapes and the walkman. That being the case... I decided, dun, dun dun! I would make my own datasette clone. Using an arduino as the brains to back it. About 25 years later, I could have my own datasette \\m/\r\n\r\nWhat tapeDuino really is; is a Casette Tape NAS, a home-brew NAS. Or if I want to explain it to my mom \"It\'s kinda like a harddrive, or a memory stick, however, when it stores data on a cassette tape, and that\'s supposed to be kinda funny. And it\'s homemade.\" Or if my wife were to explain it she\'d probably call it \"my girlfriend\" or \"a rube goldberg contraption\". And yes... It is intentionally silly; come on, a tape deck for media. The tapeDuino unit sits independent of a host, and connects to the ethernet; with a client which runs on (maybe) any *nix host with a Perl implementation.\r\n\r\nOne of the first things I was thinking of was; how am I going to store the data as tones on the tape deck?\r\n\r\nAfter some noodling about it, and being kind of a telephony weirdo myself; I decided I would use <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual-tone_multi-frequency_signaling\">DTMF</a> to store the tones onto tape. The reasons I picked DTMF are...\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>It\'s an easy existing way of storing a value with a tone that already has a spec.</li>\r\n	<li>I could use an IC to offload most of the read operation to; specifically the MT8870 [<a href=\"http://www.wulfden.org/downloads/datasheets/M-8870-01.pdf\">datasheet</a>] [<a href=\" http://www.zarlink.com/zarlink/mt8870d-datasheet-oct2006.pdf \">second datasheet</a>]</li>\r\n	<li>The DTMF spec calls for 16 symbols. Conveniently, that\'s hexadecimal. So each symbol is a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nibble\">nibble</a> (4 bits) of data.</li>\r\n	<li>It\'s kinda retro, just like a tape deck.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSo I started to do some homework. I found that <a href=\" http://razorconcepts.net/dtmf.html\">RazorConcepts had designed a PCB </a>to convert the 4 bit output of a MT8870 to decimal, which <a href=\" http://batchpcb.com/index.php/Products/27676\">you can buy on BatchPCB</a>. He also <a href=\" http://forum.allaboutcircuits.com/showthread.php?t=30775\">discussed it on a forum</a> before finalizing, which I found interesting. There\'s a also a guy who made <a href=\" http://w2mh.wordpress.com/2010/06/03/dtmf-shield/\">an Arduino shield</a> based on the RazorConcept\'s design. And this guy <a href=\" http://www.arduino.cc/cgi-bin/yabb2/YaBB.pl?num=1246431289\">posted on the Arduino.cc forum</a> about DTMF circuitry with an 8870. And another post from that forum gave me the idea to put <a href=\"http://www.arduino.cc/cgi-bin/yabb2/YaBB.pl?num=1284828366\">LEDs on the 8870\'s output pins</a>, for debug.\r\n\r\nAs for output, I do have an IC I bought from Newark, which is a DTMF generator. It\'s a <a href=\"http://www.newark.com/jsp/search/productdetail.jsp?SKU=53M7848\">Holtek HT9200A</a> [<a href=\"http://www.farnell.com/datasheets/79214.pdf\">datasheet</a>]. However, it\'s a surface mount IC, argh. Which kinda turned me off. So I went ahead with using the <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/rogue-code/wiki/ToneLibraryDocumentation\">Arduino Tone Library</a>. Which conveniently has a <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/arduino-tone/source/browse/trunk/examples/DTMFTest/DTMFTest.pde\">DTMF example sketch</a> (however, you\'ll have to go to wikipedia to get the missing 4 tones from the spec).\r\n\r\nGiven what I had found, I was ready to whip out the breadboard, and start building out the discrete elements.','tapeDuino -- the concept.','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision-2','','','2012-03-12 12:13:55','2012-03-12 12:13:55','',1,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=24',0,'revision','',0),(25,2,'2012-03-12 14:16:24','2012-03-12 18:16:24','With one of these <a href=\"https://www.rocksbarbque.com/index.html\">Rock\'s BBQ Stoker</a>, a wifi unit to stoke &amp; baffle your BBQ smoker; I could be making ribs for dinner from my desk at work. Dammmmn.\r\n\r\nYeah, it\'s a kinda robotic smoker. Not exactly quite as <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gjBXFn4-TSo\">cool as the Bum Bot</a>, which is genius. But, the stoker is probably a bit more ethical.','Smoker + WiFi Stoker + Ribs == Nirvana','','publish','open','open','','smoker-wifi-stoker-ribs-nirvana','','','2012-03-13 15:44:55','2012-03-13 19:44:55','',0,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=25',0,'post','',0),(26,1,'2012-03-12 14:15:16','2012-03-12 14:15:16','With one of these <a href=\"https://www.rocksbarbque.com/index.html\">Rock\'s BBQ Stoker</a>, a wifi unit to stoke &amp; baffle your BBQ smoker; I could be making ribs for dinner from my desk at work. Dammmmn.\n\nYeah, it\'s a kinda robotic smoker. Not exactly quite as <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gjBXFn4-TSo\">cool as the Bum Bot</a>, which is genius. But, the stoker is probably a bit more ethical.','Smoker + WiFi Stoker + Ribs == Nirvana','','inherit','open','open','','25-revision','','','2012-03-12 14:15:16','2012-03-12 14:15:16','',25,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=26',0,'revision','',0),(27,1,'2012-03-12 14:17:29','2012-03-12 14:17:29','With one of these <a href=\"https://www.rocksbarbque.com/index.html\">Rock\'s BBQ Stoker</a>, a wifi unit to stoke &amp; baffle your BBQ smoker; I could be making ribs for dinner from my desk at work. Dammmmn.\n\nYeah, it\'s a kinda robotic smoker. Not exactly quite as <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gjBXFn4-TSo\">cool as the Bum Bot</a>, which is genius. But, the stoker is probably a bit more ethical.','Smoker + WiFi Stoker + Ribs == Nirvana','','inherit','open','open','','25-autosave','','','2012-03-12 14:17:29','2012-03-12 14:17:29','',25,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=27',0,'revision','',0),(28,2,'2012-03-12 15:17:59','2012-03-12 19:17:59','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img id=\"phgallery-28_1 3\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />tapeDuino\'s birth into this world was rather rough, in all sorts of distorted breadboard reality, but... I\'m relatively happy with how the perfboard turned out. You\'ll notice the DB-9 subminiature receptacle on there at this stage. That\'s for the interface to the sony tape deck -- mostly for style points. Counter-intuitively, but, naturally... The actual data goes over the audio interface, through the 3.5mm socket.','tapeDuino: from breadboard to perfboard','','publish','open','open','','tapeduino-from-breadboard-to-perfboard','','','2012-03-13 15:44:48','2012-03-13 19:44:48','',0,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=28',0,'post','',0),(29,1,'2012-03-12 14:47:11','2012-03-12 14:47:11','','tapeDuino: from breadboard to perfboard','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision','','','2012-03-12 14:47:11','2012-03-12 14:47:11','',28,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=29',0,'revision','',0),(30,1,'2012-03-12 14:47:17','2012-03-12 14:47:17','','tapeDuino: from breadboard to perfboard','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-2','','','2012-03-12 14:47:17','2012-03-12 14:47:17','',28,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=30',0,'revision','',0),(31,1,'2012-03-12 17:14:51','2012-03-12 17:14:51','&nbsp;\n\n<img id=\"phgallery-28_1 3\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />tapeDuino\'s birth into this world was rather rough, in all sorts of distorted breadboard reality, but... I\'m relatively happy with how the perfboard turned out. You\'ll notice the DB-9 subminiature receptacle on there at this stage. That\'s for the interface to the sony tape deck -- mostly for style points. Counter-intuitively, but, naturally... The actual data goes over the audio interface, through the 3.5mm socket.','tapeDuino: from breadboard to perfboard','','inherit','open','open','','28-autosave','','','2012-03-12 17:14:51','2012-03-12 17:14:51','',28,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=31',0,'revision','',0),(32,1,'2012-03-12 15:17:59','2012-03-12 15:17:59','<img id=\"phgallery-28_1 2\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />','tapeDuino: from breadboard to perfboard','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-3','','','2012-03-12 15:17:59','2012-03-12 15:17:59','',28,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=32',0,'revision','',0),(33,1,'2012-03-12 15:19:13','2012-03-12 15:19:13','<img id=\"phgallery-28_1 3\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />','tapeDuino: from breadboard to perfboard','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-4','','','2012-03-12 15:19:13','2012-03-12 15:19:13','',28,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=33',0,'revision','',0),(34,1,'2012-03-12 15:20:06','2012-03-12 15:20:06','<img id=\"phgallery-28_1 3\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />','tapeDuino: from breadboard to perfboard','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-5','','','2012-03-12 15:20:06','2012-03-12 15:20:06','',28,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=34',0,'revision','',0),(35,1,'2012-03-12 17:08:27','2012-03-12 17:08:27','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img id=\"phgallery-28_1 3\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />tapeDuino\'s birth into this world was rather rough, in all sorts of distorted breadboard reality, but... I\'m relatively happy with how the perfboard turned out. You\'ll notice the DB-9 subminiature receptacle on there at this stage. That\'s for the interface to the sony tape deck -- mostly for style points. Counter-intuitively, but, naturally... The actual data goes over the audio interface, through the 3.5mm socket.','tapeDuino: from breadboard to perfboard','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-6','','','2012-03-12 17:08:27','2012-03-12 17:08:27','',28,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=35',0,'revision','',0),(36,1,'2012-03-12 17:09:00','2012-03-12 17:09:00','<img id=\"phgallery-28_1 3\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />\r\n\r\ntapeDuino\'s birth into this world was rather rough, in all sorts of distorted breadboard reality, but... I\'m relatively happy with how the perfboard turned out. You\'ll notice the DB-9 subminiature receptacle on there at this stage. That\'s for the interface to the sony tape deck -- mostly for style points. Counter-intuitively, but, naturally... The actual data goes over the audio interface, through the 3.5mm socket.','tapeDuino: from breadboard to perfboard','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-7','','','2012-03-12 17:09:00','2012-03-12 17:09:00','',28,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=36',0,'revision','',0),(37,2,'2012-03-12 20:13:30','2012-03-13 00:13:30','<img id=\"phgallery-37_1 3\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMany thanks to my buddy who helped me build this frame/rack! Err, really he did the building. He\'s a brain behind <a href=\"http://woodgivesmewood.com/\">woodgivesmewood.com</a> (worth a look, more than once). It\'s looking awesome, umm, ahem, <em>spee-roing</em>! which it would not\'ve had I gone at it with a handsaw and a dremel, which is what I would\'ve done if he wasn\'t so kind as to rock his skills and his bad-ass woodshop in the honor of this device.\r\n\r\nHere\'s an idea I\'ve been mulling over. In the most simple terms this is a kind of \"abacus for programmers\". I call it heroOfArduinia. It\'s based on a concept invented (or improved upon) by <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hero_of_Alexandria\">Hero of Alexandria</a>. An inventor from around 10AD. He\'s best known for his <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aeolipile\">pneumatic wonders, especially his aeolipile</a> (an <em>almost</em>-steam-engine-before-the industrial-revolution).\r\n\r\nWhat I\'m most fond of Hero for is, well... Number one is the fact that this guy made inventions which were used as a sort of magic in order to fool temple-goers into thinking the temple they were in was the most divine, or somehow, had the power of the gods. In reality: it was just bad-ass technology for it\'s day. Secondly, he invented a device which was used for sequencing. Personally, I think it\'s the world\'s first cybernetic device.\r\n<h3><em>cy·ber·net·ics</em>/ˌsībərˈnetiks/</h3>\r\n<div>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"80px\">Noun:</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\">\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>The science of communications and automatic control systems in both machines and living things.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div><BR />Yep, like that. So this is a kind of study of that device, however... Mine is going to be used a kinda turing abacus. For now, I\'ll leave it at that, as I\'ve got too much to say about it.</div>','heroOfArduinia: the beginnings','','publish','open','open','','heroofarduinia-the-beginnings','','','2012-03-13 15:44:41','2012-03-13 19:44:41','',0,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=37',0,'post','',0),(38,1,'2012-03-12 17:23:01','2012-03-12 17:23:01','','heroOfArduinia: the beginnings','','inherit','open','open','','37-revision','','','2012-03-12 17:23:01','2012-03-12 17:23:01','',37,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=38',0,'revision','',0),(39,1,'2012-03-12 17:23:22','2012-03-12 17:23:22','','heroOfArduinia: the beginnings','','inherit','open','open','','37-revision-2','','','2012-03-12 17:23:22','2012-03-12 17:23:22','',37,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=39',0,'revision','',0),(40,1,'2012-03-12 17:35:38','2012-03-12 17:35:38','<img id=\"phgallery-37_1 3\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />\n\nMany thanks to my buddy to help me build this frame/rack! He\'s a brain behind <a href=\"http://woodgivesmewood.com/\">woodgivesmewood.com</a>. It\'s looking awesome, umm, ahem, <em>spee-roing</em>! which it would not\'ve had I gone at it with a handsaw and a dremel, which is what I would\'ve done if he wasn\'t so kind as to rock his skills and his bad-ass woodshop in the honor of this device.\n\nHere\'s an idea I\'ve been mulling over in my head. In the most simple terms this is a kind of \"abacus for programmers\". I call it heroOfArduinia. It\'s based on a concept invented (or improved upon) by <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hero_of_Alexandria\">Hero of Alexandria</a>. An inventor from around 10AD. He\'s best known for his <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aeolipile\">pneumatic wonders, especially his aeolipile</a> (an <em>almost</em>-steam-engine-before-the industrial-revolution).\n\n&nbsp;','heroOfArduinia: the beginnings','','inherit','open','open','','37-revision-3','','','2012-03-12 17:35:38','2012-03-12 17:35:38','',37,'http://dougbtv.com/?p=40',0,'revision','',0),(41,1,'2012-03-12 20:13:27','2012-03-12 20:13:27','<img id=\"phgallery-37_1 3\" src=\"http://dougbtv.com/wp-content/themes/photocrati-theme/photocrati-gallery/image/gallery-placeholder-1.gif\" alt=\"photocrati gallery\" />\n\nMany thanks to my buddy to help me build this frame/rack! He\'s a brain behind <a href=\"http://woodgivesmewood.com/\">woodgivesmewood.com</a> (worth a look, more than once). It\'s looking awesome, umm, ahem, <em>spee-roing</em>! which it would not\'ve had I gone at it with a handsaw and a dremel, which is what I would\'ve done if he wasn\'t so kind as to rock his skills and his bad-ass woodshop in the honor of this device.\n\nHere\'s an idea I\'ve been mulling over. In the most simple terms this is a kind of \"abacus for programmers\". I call it heroOfArduinia. It\'s based on a concept invented (or improved upon) by <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hero_of_Alexandria\">Hero of Alexandria</a>. An inventor from around 10AD. He\'s best known for his <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aeolipile\">pneumatic wonders, especially his aeolipile</a> (an <em>almost</em>-steam-engine-before-the industrial-revolution).\n\nWhat I\'m most fond of Hero for is, well... Number one is the fact that this guy made inventions which were used as a sort of magic in order to fool temple-goers into thinking the temple they were in was the most divine, or somehow, had the power of the gods. In reality: it was just bad-ass technology for it\'s day. Secondly, he invented a device which was used for sequencing. Personally, I think it\'s the world\'s first cybernetic device.\n<h3><em>cy·ber·net·ics</em>/ˌsībərˈnetiks/</h3>\n<div>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"80px\">Noun:</td>\n<td valign=\"top\">\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>The science of communications and automatic control systems in both machines and living things.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n</div>\n<div></div>\n<div>Yep, like that. So this is a kind of study of that device, however... Mine is going to be used a kinda turing abacus. For now, I\'ll leave it at that, as I\'ve got too much to say about it.</di